"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"1bce52",
"children":[
"The hallmark of urticaria (hives) is the wheal, a superficial, pruritic, erythematous, well-demarcated, intermittently present plaque."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"fd66e1",
"children":[
"In acute urticaria, intermittent hives are present for 6 weeks or less. In chronic urticaria, intermittent hives are present for greater than 6 weeks."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a00de7",
"children":[
"Individual lesions usually disappear within hours without residual skin discoloration."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"410231",
"children":[
"Food allergy (shellfish, peanuts, tree nuts), viral infection, and medication reaction are the most common causes of acute urticaria. Infrequent but important causes of urticaria include autoimmune thyroid disease and malignancies, particularly lymphoma. Urticaria can also develop with pressure, cold, heat, vibration, water, or sunlight."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"c47357",
"children":[
"In most patients with chronic urticaria, a definite cause is not identified. Limited targeted laboratory testing is indicated when clinical suspicion suggests a cause, but routine, extensive testing should not be performed."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1501e8",
"children":[
"Do not select ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"antinuclear antibody",
"children":[
"ANA"
]
},
","
]
},
" patch testing, or specific IgE measurements for acute or chronic urticaria."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"fc6d93",
"children":[
"Painful lesions persisting >24 hours with purpura/ecchymoses on resolution are likely the result of urticarial vasculitis. Definitive diagnosis is made by skin biopsy."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
